message.content:
We must “read” through the transactions and pick out which ones “create” a liability. In our double‐entry system the beginning (“initial”) entries are the starting balance–here the “Initial20231231001” rows give only asset entries (cash, bank, fixed assets) so no liabilities are recorded initially. (Often any “initial liabilities” would be entered with a distinct type – here none appear.) 

Then we scan the rest of the transactions:
• In our “Purchase” transactions the ones that were “Paid” usually are immediately settled (and hence do not leave a liability on the balance sheet) while those that are “Unpaid” (or use a “payment method” such as “Account Payable”) must be recorded as a liability.
• In our data only two purchase transactions remain “Unpaid”:
 – “Purchase20231231005” for an amount of 460000.0 (shown with payment method “Account Payable” and a status of “Unpaid”)
 – “Purchase20231231008” for an amount of 800000.0 (again with “Unpaid” status and account‐payable payment).

No other transaction type (for example expenses and interest receivables) are “liability” transactions in our system (interest receivable is actually an asset even if not yet received).

Thus the total liability at the start is 0.00 and the remaining (end‑of‑period) liabilities are the sum:
 460000.0 + 800000.0 = 1260000.0

We then output the answer in the requested JSON format.

Below is our answer. 

--------------------------------

{"solution": {"Total Liabilities Initial Value": "0.00", "Total Liabilities End Value": "1260000.00"}}
